<BaseLayout title="optimisationblindness.org">
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="lede">
      Automated systems increasingly shape how hotels, destinations, and visitors make decisions. Each system optimises for what it can measure. The problem is what disappears outside those measurements.
    </p>

    <p class="lede">
      <strong>Optimisation blindness</strong> names that problem.
    </p>

    <p class="hierarchy">
      The work develops the concept through two measurement frameworks. <strong><a href="/revemo">RevEmo</a></strong> measures what optimisation misses inside the hotel, at the level of the guest encounter. <strong><a href="/deqi">DEQI</a></strong> measures what optimisation misses across the tourism city, at the level of the destination.
    </p>

    <p class="hierarchy">
      RevEmo and DEQI are not separate ideas. They are two applications of the same concern: that optimisation systems can create measurable value while eroding forms of value they were not designed to measure.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <p class="section-label">Formal definition</p>
    <p>
      Optimisation blindness is the property of an automated environment in which locally rational optimisation, performed by multiple systems in parallel, aggregates into outcomes that no individual system can detect, because the relevant signals are absent from any one objective function.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <p class="section-label">Recent</p>
    <ul class="recent-list">
